.\" pamsignal.8 - manual page for the pamsignal daemon
.\" Maintained as pamsignal.8.in; .TH version is filled by meson at build.
.TH PAMSIGNAL 8 "2026-05-03" "pamsignal @VERSION@" "System Manager's Manual"
.SH NAME
pamsignal \- real-time PAM authentication monitor with multi-channel alerts
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pamsignal
.RB [ \-f \ |\  \-\-foreground ]
.RB [ \-c \ |\  \-\-config
.IR PATH ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pamsignal
is a lightweight C daemon that monitors PAM authentication events through
the systemd journal. It detects login attempts, logouts, and brute-force
patterns produced by
.BR sshd (8),
.BR sudo (8),
.BR su (1),
.BR login (1),
and
.BR systemd-logind (8),
optionally dispatching alerts to Telegram, Slack, Microsoft Teams, WhatsApp,
Discord, or an arbitrary HTTPS webhook.
.PP
The daemon is designed to run under
.BR systemd (1)
as the unprivileged user
.BR pamsignal ,
which must be a member of the
.B systemd-journal
group to obtain read-only access to the journal. Outbound HTTP requests are
made via
.BR curl (1)
launched in a fork+exec child so a network failure cannot crash the parent
process.
.PP
At runtime the daemon refuses to start as
.BR root ,
caps its descendant process count to bound any alert-driven fork-burst, and
sets
.BR PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS
to refuse setuid escalation in any child it spawns. The shipped systemd
unit additionally applies
.BR ProtectSystem=strict ,
.BR MemoryDenyWriteExecute=yes ,
.BR NoNewPrivileges=yes ,
.BR CapabilityBoundingSet= ,
and a
.BR SystemCallFilter=
allowlist; see
.BR systemd.exec (5)
for the meaning of each directive.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-foreground
Stay in the foreground (do not daemonize). Required when running under a
process supervisor such as
.BR systemd (1)
with
.BR Type=simple .
This is the mode used by the shipped
.B pamsignal.service
unit. In foreground mode no PID file is created.
.TP
\fB\-c\fR \fIPATH\fR, \fB\-\-config\fR \fIPATH\fR
Read configuration from
.I PATH
instead of the compiled-in default. The path is resolved through
.BR realpath (3)
before
.BR chdir (\(dq/\(dq)
is called; an unresolvable path causes
.B pamsignal
to refuse to start (defending against symlink swaps and permission
misconfigurations).
.SH SIGNALS
.TP
.B SIGHUP
Reload the configuration file. Parsing happens into a temporary
.B ps_config_t
first; on success the new configuration is swapped in atomically. On parse
failure the previous configuration is preserved. The in-memory brute-force
tracking table is preserved across reloads, so existing per-source-IP
attempt counts and alert cooldowns survive the reload.
.TP
.B SIGTERM
Terminate gracefully. The journal watch loop returns, the PID file (if
any) is removed, and the daemon exits with status 0.
.TP
.B SIGINT
Same handling as
.BR SIGTERM .
Useful when running interactively in
.BR \-\-foreground
mode.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/pamsignal/pamsignal.conf
The configuration file. The compiled-in default path is set at meson
configure time from
.B sysconfdir
and may differ for non-system installs. The file holds alert-channel
credentials (Telegram bot tokens, webhook URLs) and brute-force tuning
parameters; it is shipped with mode
.B 0640
and group
.BR pamsignal .
See
.BR pamsignal.conf (5)
\(em or, until that page exists,
.B pamsignal.conf.example
in the source tree \(em for the full key reference.
.TP
.B /run/pamsignal/pamsignal.pid
PID file written when the daemon is launched without
.BR \-\-foreground .
Created via
.BR openat (2)
under an
.BR O_DIRECTORY \  | \  O_NOFOLLOW
directory file descriptor; a stale PID file is removed only after
.BR kill (pid,\ 0)
returns
.BR ESRCH .
The directory is supplied by the systemd unit's
.B RuntimeDirectory=pamsignal
directive.
.TP
.B /usr/lib/systemd/system/pamsignal.service
The shipped systemd service unit (vendor unit path). Admin overrides
belong in
.B /etc/systemd/system/pamsignal.service.d/*.conf
drop-ins, not on top of the vendored unit.
.SH OUTPUT
All operational logging is emitted via
.BR sd_journal_send (3)
with structured fields aligned to the Elastic Common Schema (ECS).
Useful queries:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
journalctl \-t pamsignal \-f
journalctl \-u pamsignal \-\-since today
journalctl _SYSTEMD_UNIT=pamsignal.service EVENT_ACTION=brute_force_detected
.EE
.RE
.PP
The
.B PAMSIGNAL_*
field set is retained as a backward-compatibility shim through the 0.2.x
series alongside the ECS-aligned
.BR EVENT_* / USER_* / SOURCE_* / HOST_* / SERVICE_* / PROCESS_*
fields, and is scheduled to retire in 0.3.0.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful clean shutdown (typically via SIGTERM/SIGINT).
.TP
.B 1
Refused to start: invoked as root, current user is not in the
.B systemd-journal
group, the configuration file path could not be resolved, or the
configuration file failed to load.
.TP
.B non\-zero (other)
An internal subsystem failed to initialize: signal handlers, daemonize,
PID-file acquisition, or journal watch. The detailed reason is logged via
.BR sd_journal_print (3)
to the journal under syslog identifier
.BR pamsignal .
.SH SECURITY
.B pamsignal
is a security-monitoring daemon and is itself written defensively. Notable
hardening choices:
.IP \(bu 2
Runs as a dedicated unprivileged user with read-only journal access; never
opens a listening socket; the only outbound network capability is the
.BR curl (1)
fork+exec path used for alert dispatch.
.IP \(bu 2
Alert credentials are passed to the curl child through a memfd-backed
.B \-\-config
file rather than via argv, so they do not appear in
.B /proc/<pid>/cmdline
or in process accounting.
.IP \(bu 2
Webhook URLs are constrained to
.B https://
via curl's
.B \-\-proto =https
flag.
.IP \(bu 2
Journal entries are filtered through an
.B _EXE
allowlist (\fBsshd\fR, \fBsudo\fR, \fBsu\fR, \fBlogin\fR,
\fBsystemd-logind\fR under a system prefix); entries with a missing
.B _EXE
field are dropped, so an unprivileged user cannot inject fake PAM events
via
.BR logger (1).
.IP \(bu 2
Per-source-IP brute-force tracking with a configurable cooldown bounds the
alert volume during a sustained attack.
.IP \(bu 2
Local privilege-escalation brute-force tracking. Failed
.BR sudo (8)
and
.BR su (1)
authentications are keyed by the local actor (\fIruser\fR from the
.B pam_unix
auth-failure message); the chat alert reports
.IR actor ,
.IR target ,
.IR attempts ,
and
.I service
when the threshold is crossed. Per-event chat alerts are suppressed for
sudo/su login failures (the journal entry is still written so
.B journalctl
history is complete) — only the threshold-breach alert fires, so a
single mistyped password does not page the operator.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR pamsignal.conf (5),
.BR systemctl (1),
.BR systemd.exec (5),
.BR systemd.unit (5),
.BR journalctl (1),
.BR sd_journal_send (3),
.BR sshd_config (5),
.BR pam (8)
.SH BUGS
Report bugs at <https://github.com/anhtuank7c/pamsignal/issues>.
.SH AUTHOR
Tuan Nguyen <anhtuank7c@hotmail.com>
